From Geoffrey Sherwood Subject Re Monitors Nanao Adrie Koolen wrote In article Brian J Schaufenbuel writes What tube does the Viewsonic use Does is support I've been looking a a Philips which uses a Sony Trinitron tube has digital controls supports up to and has dot pitch It can be found for under The original poster John Navitsky said that he might use the monitor on a SparcStation The LX is able to generate a picture at at Not officially but I tried to set this resolution and refresh rate and the LX came up with a non syncing Our tube obviously couldn't handle this At Hz it worked I don't know which tube the Viewsonic uses but it has an horizontal bandwidth so you can go pretty I ran mine at which was as fast as the Orchid could drive Also the does claim to be able to support but I have no experience with Since I have the spec sheet in front of me I'll type some in CRT mm dot pitch deg deflection RGB mediou short persisance Tint TM anti static anti glare anti reflection Input Signal RGB Analog p ohms also has setting for p Sync H V Separate ttl composite sync on green horizontal freq vertical freq compatibility PC from VGA to non interlaced mac IIci and above controls contrast brightness position size degauss p p voltage color temp sync select color tuning moire on video band witdth MHz Max brightness cd at white flat field misconvergence max at center max at corner dimensions weight lbs I don't know what some of those mean and don't verify their accuracy I just typed them Other things they hype on the sheet are a 'double quaduple dynamic astigmatism focus' They mean they use two Advanced Invar shadow ViewMatch color control which they claim is and easy to use system that adjusts colors to closely match printer As near as I have been able to figure out this translates to separate controls for red green and How this makes it easy to match for printer output is beyond But beyond the hype the monitor is very pleasant to look Sharp clear and isn't nearly as bad as the NEC's for geoff sherwood